            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Examples and applications › Cohomology of groups and of classifying spaces"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii-9.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii-9" title="Hodge Theory III › Examples and applications"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Examples and applications</fr:link> › Cohomology of groups and of classifying spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>9.1</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a complex connected linear algebraic group.
  We intend to calculated the mixed Hodge structure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (G)]]></fr:tex>.
  We will start by calculating that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G})]]></fr:tex>, by reduction to the case of tori;
  we will then calculate that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (G)]]></fr:tex> via the Eilenberg–Moore spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.5.xml" number="6.1.5" />.
  As a bonus, we obtain the strange Theorem [hodge-theory-iii-9.1.7 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>].</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2455</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>9.1.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a linear algebraic group.
    We have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2n+1}(\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G},\mathbb {Q})=0]]></fr:tex>, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2n}(\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G},\mathbb {Q})\otimes \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is pure of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n,n)]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-0.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-0.5.xml" number="III.0.5" />)</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2159</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#236</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-236.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G^0]]></fr:tex> be the identity component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T\subset  G^0]]></fr:tex> be a maximal torus.
      Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G},\mathbb {Q})=\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G^0},\mathbb {Q})^{G/G^0}]]></fr:tex>, we have, by the <fr:em>splitting principle</fr:em> (see <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.xml" number="6.1.6" />)
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G},\mathbb {Q})         \hookrightarrow  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  T},\mathbb {Q}).       ]]></fr:tex>
      This inclusion is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures: it suffices to consider the case of a torus, or even, by the Künneth formula, the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G=\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}]]></fr:tex>.
      Here are two proofs of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-9.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-9.1.1.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="9.1.1" /> in this case.</fr:p>

    <fr:p><fr:em>1st proof.</fr:em> —
      The cohomology of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}]]></fr:tex> (i.e. of the projective line minus two points) is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^0=\operatorname {H}^1=\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
      The only Hodge numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{pq}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m})]]></fr:tex> that can be non-zero are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{01}=h^{10}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{11}]]></fr:tex> ((i) and (iv) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.2.4" />).
      Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{01}+h^{10}+h^{11}=2h^{01}+h^{11}=1]]></fr:tex>, we have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{01}=0]]></fr:tex>, and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m})]]></fr:tex> is pure of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(1,1)]]></fr:tex> (for another proof, see [hodge-theory-iii-10.3.8 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>]).
      The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_2^{p,q}]]></fr:tex> page of the spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.5.xml" number="6.1.5" />, which is zero for odd <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+q]]></fr:tex>, is thus pure of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[((p+q)/2,(p+q)/2)]]></fr:tex>.
      Its abutment has the same homogeneity.</fr:p>

    <fr:p><fr:em>2nd proof.</fr:em> —
      We know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {P}^r(\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex>, endowed with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}(1)]]></fr:tex>, is an "approximation" of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {B}_{\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}}]]></fr:tex>: the homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathcal {O}(1)]\colon \operatorname {H}^i(\mathrm {B}_{\bullet \mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}})\to \operatorname {H}^i(\mathbb {P}^r(\mathbb {C}))]]></fr:tex> is bijective for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\leqslant  2r]]></fr:tex>.
      The cohomology group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2i}(\mathbb {P}^r(\mathbb {C}))]]></fr:tex> is generated by the cohomology class of an algebraic cycle (that is, a linear subspace), and is thus of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(i,i)]]></fr:tex>.
      The following proposition allows us to deduce that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2i}(\mathrm {B}_{\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}})]]></fr:tex> is of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(i,i)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2456</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>9.1.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be an algebraic group (over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>), and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> a (algebraic) principal homogeneous space with group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> over a scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       [P]\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_G)=\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G})       \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)     ]]></fr:tex>
    is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2438</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#237</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-237.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>This follows from the definition (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.3.1" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[P]]]></fr:tex> and from functoriality (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4.xml" taxon="Definition" number="8.3.4" />).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2457</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>9.1.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The characteristic classes, in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2n}(S)]]></fr:tex>, of a (algebraic) principal homogeneous space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, with structure group a linear group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, are pure of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n,n)]]></fr:tex>: they come from morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}(-n)\to \operatorname {H}^{2n}(S,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In the particular case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is smooth and quasi-projective, we know that the characteristic classes of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> are even algebraic, i.e. in the image of the Chow ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\otimes \mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
